</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="39" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="39">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="39">
This genus includes about 280 species in the world and is the largest genus in the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="12" pageNumber="39" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Thripinae">Thripinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation pageId="12" pageNumber="39">ThripsWiki 2013</bibRefCitation>
), and includes 29 species in Iran (
<bibRefCitation author="Mirab-balou, M" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Insect Sciences" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" pagination="1 - 15" title="A new record and new species of the genus Thrips (Thysanoptera: Thripidae), with a key to species from Iran." url="10.1673/031.012.9001" volume="12" year="2012 a">Mirab-balou et al. 2012a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Minaei, K" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Entomological and Acarological Research" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" pagination="42 - 45" title="First report of an endemic Australian thrips, Thrips australis (Thysanoptera: Thripidae) on Eucalyptus in Shiraz, Iran." url="10.4081/jear.2012.e9" volume="44" year="2012 c">Minaei 2012c</bibRefCitation>
). The genus shows extensive diversity in most parts of the world except the Neotropical region, and includes many species of economic importance (
<bibRefCitation author="Bhatti, JS" journalOrPublisher="SystematicEntomology" pageId="12" pageNumber="39" pagination="109 - 166" title="Species of the genus Thrips from India (Thysanoptera)." url="10.1111/j.1365-3113.1980.tb00404.x" volume="5" year="1980">Bhatti 1980</bibRefCitation>
). Several species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Thrips</taxonomicName>
are considered crop pests in various parts of the world, such as 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thrips angusticeps" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angusticeps">Thrips angusticeps</taxonomicName>
Uzel, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thrips flavus" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavus">Thrips flavus</taxonomicName>
Schrank, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thrips hawaiiensis" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hawaiiensis">Thrips hawaiiensis</taxonomicName>
(Morgan), 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thrips meridionalis" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">Thrips meridionalis</taxonomicName>
Priesner, and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thrips tabaci" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tabaci">Thrips tabaci</taxonomicName>
Lindeman (
<bibRefCitation pageId="12" pageNumber="39">Moritz et al. 2001</bibRefCitation>
). The latter species is well known as the most important pest of onion crops, greenhouses and ornamental plants in Iran (
<bibRefCitation author="Mirab-balou, M" journalOrPublisher="Natura Montenegrina" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" pagination="435 - 466" title="Iranian Thripinae with ctenidia laterally on the abdominal tergites (Thysanoptera: Thripidae)." volume="10" year="2011 a">Mirab-balou and Chen 2011a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mirab-balou, M" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Insect Science" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" pagination="1 - 7" title="A new species of Scirtothrips infesting Ginkgo biloba in eastern China." url="10.1673/031.012.11701" volume="12" year="2012 b">Mirab-balou et al. 2012b</bibRefCitation>
), and is a vector of some Tospovirus diseases on plants.
</paragraph>
